---
/**
 * Our Story — the estate's story, land, house, philosophy and mission.
 * Copy adapted from Docs/our-story-estate-voice.md (Maremma estate voice).
 */
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import PageHero from "../components/PageHero.astro";
import SplitSection from "../components/SplitSection.astro";
import SectionHeader from "../components/SectionHeader.astro";
import StatBand from "../components/StatBand.astro";
import QuoteBand from "../components/QuoteBand.astro";
import Button from "../components/Button.astro";
import Reveal from "../components/Reveal.astro";
import { bookingHref } from "../data/site";
import { photos } from "../data/media";

const estateStats = [
  { value: "3,000", label: "Years of view" },
  { value: "40", label: "Acres of estate" },
  { value: "5", label: "Private suites" },
  { value: "1", label: "View of the sea" },
];

const values = [
  {
    title: "Rootedness",
    body: "Of this place, from this place, for this place.",
  },
  {
    title: "Continuity",
    body: "Traditions kept in use, not kept in glass.",
  },
  {
    title: "Hospitality",
    body: "In the old Tuscan sense. A guest at the table is family at the table.",
  },
  {
    title: "Stillness",
    body: "Guarded on this hill as carefully as any monument.",
  },
  {
    title: "Wonder",
    body: "The daily kind. A sunset behind Corsica never becomes routine.",
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Our Story"
  description="Villa Dolce Vita sits high on the Colline Metallifere in the Maremma — three thousand years of view, forty acres of olive groves and forest, five suites, and a single purpose: a front-row seat to the real Tuscany."
>
  <PageHero
    eyebrow="Our Story"
    title="The Maremma Was Here First"
    image={photos.hillsPinkDawn}
    imageAlt="Estate hills at first light, the sea on the horizon"
  >
    <p>
      This is old country. The Etruscans mined these metal-bearing hills three
      thousand years ago. The butteri, Tuscany's last working cowboys, still
      herd cattle on horseback across the plains below. Through all of it, the
      same view held.
    </p>
  </PageHero>

  <!-- THE LAND -->
  <SplitSection
    eyebrow="The Land"
    title="Where Tuscany Keeps Its Wildness"
    image={photos.landMaremmaHilltown}
    imageAlt="A medieval hilltown rising over the wild Maremma valley"
    arch
    reverse
  >
    <p>
      The Maremma is the Tuscany that stayed itself — less discovered than
      Chianti, more untamed than the Val d'Orcia. Turquoise lakes rest in the
      old mining ground. Trails run through chestnut woods. The coast, forty
      minutes away, empties out by evening.
    </p>
    <p>
      The estate sits at the centre of it, high on the Colline Metallifere.
      Forty acres of olive groves, pine and forest, threaded with walking paths
      that all end the same way — at a view. The sea lies in one direction, the
      hills in every other, and nothing stands between you and either.
    </p>
  </SplitSection>

  <!-- THE HOUSE -->
  <div class="house-split">
  <SplitSection
    eyebrow="The House"
    title="An Ancient Hill, Newly Kept"
    image={photos.houseTerraceView}
    imageAlt="A terrace table set against the estate's hillside view"
    theme="stone"
  >
    <p>
      The hill is three thousand years old. The house does not rest on that.
      Every suite has been renovated recently and completely, to one standard
      held throughout: marble bathrooms, new beds dressed in fine linens, fully
      fitted kitchens, and fine art on the walls — chosen the way everything
      here is chosen, deliberately and to last.
    </p>
    <p>
      The pairing is a rare one. A landscape that has never changed, and rooms
      that have never been newer.
    </p>
    <div class="actions">
      <Button href="/suites" variant="ghost">See the suites</Button>
    </div>
  </SplitSection>
  </div>

  <!-- BY THE NUMBERS -->
  <StatBand
    eyebrow="The Estate in Numbers"
    title="Three Thousand Years, Forty Acres"
    stats={estateStats}
    theme="dark"
  />

  <!-- THE HILLTOP -->
  <SplitSection
    eyebrow="The Hilltop"
    title="Rest, at Altitude"
    image={photos.hilltopRest}
    imageAlt="Rest at altitude — the estate's hilltop gardens and view"
    arch
    reverse
  >
    <p>
      The wellness of this place begins with the setting and is finished with
      care. A pool rests in the quiet of the hilltop gardens. A handcrafted
      barrel sauna faces the olive groves — heat and silence and landscape
      working together. An outdoor gym waits under the open sky, for those who
      prefer their stillness earned.
    </p>
    <p>
      The terraces do what terraces here have always done. They hold the view:
      the valley, the sea, the islands, and each evening a sunset that sinks
      behind Corsica and hands the sky to the stars. There is no light up here
      to argue with them. The Tuscan night arrives whole.
    </p>
  </SplitSection>

  <!-- CINEMATIC QUOTE BAND -->
  <QuoteBand
    image={photos.monteriggioni}
    imageAlt="The estate above the Maremma, the view unbroken for three thousand years"
    quote="The view is the entertainment, as it has been for three thousand years."
    cite="Villa Dolce Vita"
  />

  <!-- OUR PHILOSOPHY -->
  <SplitSection
    eyebrow="Our Philosophy"
    title="Continuity Over Novelty"
    image={photos.butteriRider}
    imageAlt="A buttero riding the Maremma plains, a tradition kept in use"
  >
    <p>
      Nothing here chases a trend. The paths follow the contours they always
      have. Dinner runs long because dinner here has always run long. The view
      is the entertainment, as it has been for three thousand years.
    </p>
    <p>
      The estate was never conceived as a resort. It is a home that opens its
      doors — more personal than a hotel, more considered than a villa for rent,
      and truer than either. Its work is not to invent an experience of Tuscany
      but to keep a real one intact, and to hold the gate open.
    </p>
  </SplitSection>

  <!-- MISSION & VALUES -->
  <section class="section bg-ivory creed-section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <SectionHeader
        eyebrow="Our Mission"
        title="To Keep This Corner of the Maremma as It Is"
        align="center"
      >
        <p>
          Its land, its light, its pace, and its evenings under the Tuscan
          stars — and to share it with guests who came for the real thing.
        </p>
      </SectionHeader>

      <ul class="values">
        {
          values.map((v, i) => (
            <Reveal as="li" class="values__item" delay={i * 0.06}>
              <span class="values__num">{String(i + 1).padStart(2, "0")}</span>
              <h3 class="values__title">{v.title}</h3>
              <p class="values__body">{v.body}</p>
            </Reveal>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- INVITATION -->
  <section class="section bg-charcoal invite">
    <div class="wrap wrap--narrow" style="text-align:center">
      <SectionHeader
        eyebrow="The Invitation"
        title="Three Thousand Years of View"
        align="center"
        onDark
      >
        <p style="color:var(--text-on-dark-muted)">
          The Etruscans chose these hills. So did the butteri. The door is open.
        </p>
      </SectionHeader>
      <Reveal delay={0.15}>
        <Button href={bookingHref} variant="secondary" onDark>Check Availability</Button>
      </Reveal>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* Scale the arched section images down ~20% and centre them in their column. */
  :global(.split .arch) {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
  }
  :global(.split .arch__frame) {
    width: 80%;
  }

  /* "The House" uses a plain (non-arch) image — scale it down ~20% and centre
     it in its column so it matches the arched sections' visual weight. */
  .house-split :global(.split__media) {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
  }
  .house-split :global(.split__img) {
    width: 80%;
  }

  /* Mission header stays on the ivory section; only the values grid below is a
     dark forest ground with the FeatureBar hover behaviour. */
  .creed-section :global(.sechead p) {
    color: var(--text-muted);
  }
  .values {
    list-style: none;
    margin: var(--space-group) 0 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(15rem, 1fr));
    background: var(--bg-dark);
    border: 1px solid var(--line-on-dark);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  /* NOTE: .values__item is rendered by <Reveal as="li">, so it does NOT carry
     this page's scope hash — target it (and its children) with :global(). */
  .values :global(.values__item) {
    position: relative;
    background: var(--bg-dark);
    padding: clamp(1.8rem, 3vw, 2.6rem);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    border-left: 1px solid var(--line-on-dark);
    transition: background var(--dur-fast) var(--ease-out);
  }
  .values :global(.values__item:first-child) {
    border-left: 0;
  }
  /* Accent line that grows up from the bottom on hover (matches FeatureBar). */
  .values :global(.values__item)::after {
    content: "";
    position: absolute;
    left: 50%;
    bottom: 0;
    width: 0;
    height: 2px;
    background: var(--accent);
    transform: translateX(-50%);
    transition: width var(--dur-fast) var(--ease-out);
  }
  .values :global(.values__item:hover) {
    background: rgba(243, 238, 230, 0.05);
  }
  .values :global(.values__item:hover)::after {
    width: 100%;
  }
  .values :global(.values__num) {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    color: var(--accent);
  }
  .values :global(.values__title) {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(1.3rem, 1.1rem + 0.7vw, 1.7rem);
    line-height: 1.1;
    color: var(--c-ivory);
    transition: color var(--dur-fast) var(--ease-out);
  }
  .values :global(.values__item:hover) .values__title {
    color: var(--accent);
  }
  .values :global(.values__body) {
    color: var(--text-on-dark-muted);
    line-height: 1.5;
    font-size: 0.98rem;
    transition: color var(--dur-fast) var(--ease-out);
  }
  .values :global(.values__item:hover) .values__body {
    color: var(--c-ivory);
  }
  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .values :global(.values__item:nth-child(odd)) {
      border-left: 0;
    }
  }
</style>
